                    {{!-- .......................Facilitation Note.............................. --}}

                    <button type="button" class="btn custom-btn w-100" data-bs-toggle="modal"
                        data-bs-target="#facilitationModal">
                        Facilitation Note
                    </button>

                    <div class="modal fade" id="facilitationModal" tabindex="-1">
                        <div class="modal-dialog modal-dialog-centered modal-lg modal-dialog-scrollable">

                            <div class="modal-content rounded-3">

                                <!-- Header -->
                                <div class="modal-header">
                                    <h3 class="modal-title fw-bold">Facilitation Notes</h3>
                                    <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal"></button>
                                </div>

                                <!-- Body -->
                                <div class="modal-body text-start">
                                    <h5 class="fw-semibold mb-3">Logistics</h5>
                                    <ul class="ps-3">
                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            Each session lasts between 40 to 50 minutes, depending upon the number of
                                            students and their learning ability.
                                        </li>

                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            The main resources for the program are 30 phonics reading charts that must
                                            be put up on walls during sessions. If possible, keep the charts up on the
                                            walls for students to read them during their free time. Make one or two
                                            students responsible for the safety of the charts.
                                        </li>

                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            Intersperse phonics reading charts activities with reading/speaking
                                            activities. We have a set of matching cards, speaking activities and books
                                            that can be used to make classes engaging (See Annexure 1-12).
                                        </li>

                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            The sessions mentioned are only for an estimate or a plan. There is a lot of
                                            overlap between charts and sessions. A single session could be used for
                                            teaching multiple charts.
                                        </li>

                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            If a class doesn’t catch up in a particular objective, feel free to roll
                                            back, slow down and repeat. There is enough flexibility in the program to
                                            revisit previous charts.
                                        </li>

                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            Comprehension of sentences is as important as being able to read. Ensure
                                            that every sentence is not just read, but understood as well.
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>

                                    <h5 class="fw-semibold mb-3">Dealing with Struggling Students</h5>
                                    <ul class="ps-3">
                                        <li class="mb-2">Remember, anyone can teach a student who already has a good
                                            base in reading. A good
                                            facilitator/teacher is one who can help struggling students catch up and
                                            learn to read. This is the main objective of a FiRST PiCk Phonics
                                            facilitator.</li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            If a student or two are struggling, seek help from other students to bring
                                            them up to the
                                            level during their free time. Most student like the additional
                                            responsibility and want to
                                            teach others.
                                        </li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            If there are two of you facilitating a class, split the class into two
                                            groups. Paying attention
                                            to individual students helps them learn faster
                                        </li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            It is likely that a few students do not catch up despite personal attention.
                                            Discuss these
                                            situations with the class teacher, who can then help you decide the best
                                            course of action.
                                            This is especially relevant for students with intellectual or reading
                                            disabilities because we
                                            are not equipped to deal with these issues.
                                        </li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">
                                            Appreciate effort made by students. Use appreciation words like “very good”
                                            often and
                                            encourage students to clap for each other. If a struggling student makes
                                            progress,
                                            highlight it to the entire class and applaud the achievement.
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>

                                    <h5 class="fw-semibold mb-3">Dealing with Indiscipline</h5>
                                    <ul class="ps-3">
                                        <li class="mb-2">Two key elements to facilitate learning in young students is
                                            engagement and lack of fear.
                                            Facilitators must not use verbal or physical violence of any kind. If a
                                            class is unruly or
                                            inattentive, it is the facilitator’s task to get their attention by changing
                                            the activity being
                                            done, or by adding elements of engagement in their teaching. Only in
                                            exceptional cases
                                            should students be asked to leave the class, after consulting with the class
                                            teacher. </li>
                                    </ul>

                                    <h5 class="fw-semibold mb-3 mt-5">Fostering Cooperation Versus Competition</h5>
                                    <ul class="ps-3">
                                        <li class="mb-2">Unlike school education, where competition among students is
                                            the motivator, the FiRST
                                            PiCk Phonics program considers cooperation as its cornerstone. Facilitators
                                            must never let
                                            any student feel they are better or worse than others.</li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">A student who comprehends a certain concept faster than others
                                            should be encouraged
                                            to teach others. Applaud cooperation and empathy towards fellow classmates
                                            more than
                                            individual achievements. </li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">Individual competitions should never be used to encourage
                                            learning. Use team
                                            competitions, which foster cooperation among team members while competing
                                            with
                                            another team. </li>
                                    </ul>

                                    <h5 class="fw-semibold mb-3 mt-5">Progress Tracking and Annual Performance</h5>
                                    <ul class="ps-3">
                                        <li class="mb-2">Before implementing the Phonics Program, we conduct a Reading
                                            Assessment (Annexure
                                            12). This gives us an idea of the current reading levels of students. The
                                            same Assessment
                                            is conducted at the end of the year and the progress of the students is
                                            recorded. </li>
                                        <li class="mb-2">Most primary school children in rural India will never have the
                                            opportunity to come on
                                            stage and perform. FiRST PiCk, being primarily a theatre and poetry club,
                                            provides such an
                                            opportunity to students, combining theatre with English reading and
                                            speaking. The FiRST
                                            PiCk Phonics Program in every school must culminate in an annual function
                                            that includes
                                            skits, plays, poems, dances and reading activities, all in English. </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>

